---
title: "How to Build a Church Operations System That Runs Without Full-Time Admin Staff"
date: "2023-04-12"
summary: "Build a church operations system that runs without full-time admin staff. Design for volunteers and part-time staff."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Church Tech"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your church operations depend on one full-time administrator. When they are out, things fall apart. The system is a person. The person is the bottleneck.

A church operations system that runs without full-time admin staff is designed for volunteers. Not for professionals. For volunteers.

Implementing this structure effectively requires a systematic, three-step methodology:

Simplify the [workflows](/process). Church [workflows](/process) are often complex because they were designed by professionals. Simplify them. A volunteer should be able to complete a task in under 10 minutes. Not 30.

Automate the reminders. Volunteers forget. The system should remind them. Not a person. The system. A reminder 24 hours before the task. A reminder the morning of.

Document the processes. Not in a manual. In the system. The system guides the volunteer through the process. Step by step. The volunteer does not need to read a manual. The system is the manual.

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2024, we built a church operations system. The church had been dependent on one administrator. We simplified the workflows. We automated the reminders. We documented the processes in the system. The administrator's role shifted from operator to overseer. The church could operate when she was out.

The teams that depend on a person are the ones that break when the person is out. The teams that depend on a system are the ones that continue.

Simplify the workflows. Automate the reminders. Document in the system. The church runs.
